Using Python to Analyze River Patterns and Deposits¶

A Jupyter notebook developed by Cole M. Speed, Spring 2019¶

This notebook documents a workflow for quantifying parameters of meandering rivers and exploring trends in geomorphology. The data for this project is a ~2m horizontal and 0.2m vertical resolution digital elevation model (DEM) generated from light detection and ranging (LiDAR) data over the Ivalo River, a meandering river system located in northern Finland. QGIS was used to digitize channel centerlines and scroll bar profiles. These data were exported from QGIS as X,Y,Z .csv files and imported to this notebook for analysis.

I have chosen two meander bends along the river extent which, through time, have transitioned from translational (downstream migrating) to expansional (migrating perpendicular to the channel belt axis). I am interested in how the geometry of the river bends relates to the elevation of the deposits that they leave behind (i.e. point bars).

While this project is focused on the morphology of river meanders, a similar workflow could be adapted for other geospatial and geomorphologic problems.

Study area - Portion of the Ivalo River, south of Ivalo, Finland¶

Shown below is an annotated image of a digital elevation model (DEM) derived from 2 m horizontal and 0.2 m vertical resolution light detection and ranging (LiDAR) data. These data were acquired by the National Land Survey of Finland (https://tiedostopalvelu.maanmittauslaitos.fi/tp/kartta?lang=en). In this study we focus on two meander bends of the Ivalo River, northern Finland.

Shown in red is the modern channel centerline. Yellow lines indicate 17 scroll bars selected across the point bar deposits of each meander bend. Digitization of the channel centerline and scroll bars was performed in QGIS (https://www.qgis.org/en/site/), a free and open source geographic information system.

Using QGIS, I digitized the features of interest and extracted elevation values from the underlying DEM at each x,y location. These data were exported as .csv files with columns corresponding to x,y,z positions. For reference, the coordinate system for this project is ETRS89 / TM35FIN(N,E), EPSG:5048. All data are in units of meters.

Figure 1. Study area and features of interest including modern channel centerline (red) and 17 scroll bars (yellow) across the two meander bends.

Compute the curvature of the channel centerline using a function created called curvature()¶

One parameter of interest is the channel curvature, which has been shown to be, in some way, related to the migration rate of rivers (e.g., Sylvester et al., 2019). It is computed as follows (function adopted from workflow developed by Z. Sylvester).

In [450]:
def curvature(x,y):
    """function computes curvature of curve defined in x and y space.
    The curvature is returned in units of 1/(unit of x and y).
    The distance along curve, s, is also computed and returned"""
    dx = np.gradient(x); dy = np.gradient(y)  # first derivatives    
    ds = np.sqrt(dx**2+dy**2) #compute arc length
    ddx = np.gradient(dx); ddy = np.gradient(dy) # second derivatives 
    curvature = (dx*ddy - dy*ddx) / ((dx**2 + dy**2)**1.5) # curvature
    s = np.cumsum(ds) # along-channel distance
    return curvature, s

Smooth the channel centerline to remove false inflection points¶

Because the channel centerline should only have two inflection points per bend, I used a Savitzky-Golay (SG) to smooth the digitized lines to eliminate the user-error induced inflection point artifacts. The SG filter is a digital filter that subsets the data based on user input and fits low ordered polynomials to theses subsets. This results in an overall smoother curve. I used visual inspection to determine if the degree of smoothing was adaquate. This could be automated if I gave it a threshold value for curvature.

To perform this analysis for all 17 scroll bars, I wrote a function compute_bar_params()¶

The function below takes the digitized curve, the window length, and the order polynomial to use for the Savitzky-Golay filter as arguments. It performs the same steps as shown above in detail. Importantly, every parameter that is calculated is returned in a dataframe at the end of the function which promotes further statistical analysis in subsequent steps.

In [470]:
def compute_bar_params(bar_profile,sw,order):
    
    #apply smoothing using the Savitzky-Golay filter method
    bar_profile['savgol_xnew'] = sp.signal.savgol_filter(bar_profile.x, sw,order)
    bar_profile['savgol_ynew'] = sp.signal.savgol_filter(bar_profile.y, sw,order)
    
    #compute curvature for the smoothed profile (created from savgol filter)
    (bar_profile['curvature_savgol'],bar_profile['s_savgol'])=curvature(bar_profile.savgol_xnew,bar_profile.savgol_ynew)
    
    
    #convert the column of the pandas dataframe to a numpy array for the next steps
    bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np = np.matrix(bar_profile.curvature_savgol)
    bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np = bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np.transpose()
    
    #inflection values of interpolated curve using savgol filter 
    inf_savgol = []
    inf_s_savgol = []
    inf_x = 0
    inf_y = 0

    if bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np[0,0] < 0:
        bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np= bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np[::-1]

        
    #the steps below were how I chose to identify inflection points, by a change of sign.    
    last_sign = 1
    
    for i,val in enumerate(bar_profile_curvature_savgol_np):
        if val == 0:
            sign = -1
            
        else:
            sign = val/abs(val)
        
        if sign != last_sign:
            inf_savgol.append(bar_profile.z[i])
            inf_s_savgol.append(bar_profile.s_savgol[i])
            inf_x = bar_profile.x[i]
            inf_y = bar_profile.y[i]
            break


    #plotting with subplots
    fig=plt.figure(figsize=(20,10))    
    
    ax2=fig.add_subplot(1,2,1)
    ax2.set_ylim([bar_profile.y.min(), bar_profile.y.max()])
    ax2.plot(bar_profile.x,bar_profile.y,'o',markersize=10,fillstyle='none',label='Digitized Bar Profile Nodes')
    ax2.plot(bar_profile.savgol_xnew,bar_profile.savgol_ynew,'-r',Linewidth='4',label='Smoothed Centerline')
    ax2.plot(inf_x,inf_y,'or',markersize=15,label='Inflection Point')
    ax2.ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='both', scilimits=None)

    ax2.set_xlabel('X(m)')
    ax2.set_ylabel('Y(m)')
    
    plt.legend(loc='best')
    plt.ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='both', scilimits=None)
    ax2.ticklabel_format(axis='both', style='plain', scilimits=None, useOffset=None, useLocale=None, useMathText=None)


    ax4=fig.add_subplot(1,2,2)
    im = ax4.scatter(bar_profile.s_savgol,bar_profile.z,c=bar_profile.curvature_savgol,s=10,cmap = plt.cm.viridis,label=None)
    fig.colorbar(im,ax=ax4)
    

    ax4.scatter(inf_s_savgol,inf_savgol,c='r',s=120,label='Inflection Point')
    ax4.set_xlabel('Distance along Bar (m)')
    ax4.set_ylabel('Elevation (m)')
    plt.legend(loc='best')


    print('Number of inflection points:',len(inf_savgol))

    return bar_profile

Let's look at some statistics for each meander bend¶

We are interested in the relationship between curvature and elevation for the meander bends and their deposits. We need to compile and organize the data for further analysis. First, I write a simple function which identifies the maximum and minimum curvature and elevation for each of the digitized scroll bar profiles.

In [491]:
#compute max and mean curvature and elevation for each profile
def curv_max_mean(bar_profile):
    max_curv = abs(bar_profile.curvature_savgol.max())
    mean_curv = abs(bar_profile.curvature_savgol.mean())
    
    max_elev = bar_profile.z.max()
    mean_elev = bar_profile.z.mean()

    bp = np.array([max_curv,mean_curv,max_elev,mean_elev])
    
    return bp

Conclusion¶

In this Jupyter Notebook,we read in data obtained through manual digitzation of river centerlines and scroll bars on top of point bars of two meander bends. We then computed various parameters including the curvature and inflection points for the channel centerline and scroll bars. Because of unavoidable user error in the digitization process, we smoothed the curves using a Savitzky-Golay digital filter.

We found that there is a sharp decrease in elevation of the bar at the point of inflection for each of the profiles. Furthermore, we find through cross-plotting various statistics that there appears to be an overall increase in elevation toward the modern location of the channel and a decrease in curvature accompanies this in each meander bend, corresponding to the transition from meander bend translation to expansion. Finally, there appears to be a positive correlation between the elevation and curvature of the scroll bars for both meander bends. This suggests that the geometry of a meandering river and the elevation of the deposits that it leaves behind are coupled.

References¶

Sylvester, Z., Durkin, P.R., and Covault, J.A., 2019, High curvatures drive river meandering: Geology , v. 47, p. 263266.
